        beginner: "Abstraction means hiding details and working with a simpler idea. In Python, when you use a function or a class, you don't need to know exactly how it works inside—you just use its name and inputs.",
        intermediate: "Abstraction is the practice of hiding implementation details behind a clear interface. In Python, functions abstract a block of logic behind a name and parameters; classes abstract state and behavior. Good abstraction lets you change how something works without breaking code that uses it. For example, you might replace a list with a database-backed object; if the interface (e.g. append, iterate) stays the same, callers are unaffected. Layers of abstraction (e.g. 'open a file' vs 'read bytes from disk') make programs easier to reason about and maintain.",
        expert: "Step 1: Identify the essential operations and invariants your caller needs. Step 2: Expose only those via a minimal interface (functions, methods, or protocol). Step 3: Implement the interface with whatever internal representation you need (e.g. in-memory list, lazy generator, or remote service). Step 4: Document preconditions and postconditions so abstraction boundaries are clear. Example: an abstract 'cache' might guarantee get(key) and set(key, value); whether it uses a dict, Redis, or a file is hidden. This allows swapping implementations for testing (e.g. mock cache) or scaling without changing call sites.",
